<paragraph id="DD15DD161411FFB08D8C4DEDEA1085D5" blockId="3.[151,758,951,1012]" box="[151,304,986,1012]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<figureCitation id="4591C1931411FFB08D8C4DEDEA1085D5" box="[151,304,986,1012]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[232,1362,207,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[221,1372,197,1887]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Figs. 1 – 8, Alisotrichia cainguas, n. sp.: 1: Head, dorsal view. 2: Maxillary palp. Figs. 3 – 5, abdominal segment VIII: 3: ventral. 4: lateral. 5: abdominal segments VIII – X, dorsal. Figs. 6 – 7: abdominal segment IX: 6: lateral. 7: ventral. 8: phallus. Figs. 9 – 12, Metrichia pitu, n. sp., male genitalia: 9: lateral. 10: ventral. 11: dorsal. 12: phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189022/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
Figures 
<number id="6B62CF311411FFB08DED4DEDEA1085D5" box="[246,304,986,1012]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="10.5" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="9.0">9–12</number>
</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="95B08E9D1411FFB08D8C4A10E80B8371" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" type="description">
<paragraph id="DD15DD161411FFB08D8C4A10E80B8371" blockId="3.[151,1437,1063,1905]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis id="EFDE01041411FFB08D8C4A10EBFD8260" bold="true" box="[151,221,1063,1089]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Male.</emphasis>
Forewing length 2.1 mm. Coloration of the body (in alcohol) dark grayish brown. Abdominal sternum VII with a spine. Segment VIII annular, becoming narrower towards the venter, where it is reduced to a thin medial strip (
<figureCitation id="4591C1931411FFB08C234A42EAA382AE" box="[312,387,1141,1167]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[232,1362,207,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[221,1372,197,1887]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Figs. 1 – 8, Alisotrichia cainguas, n. sp.: 1: Head, dorsal view. 2: Maxillary palp. Figs. 3 – 5, abdominal segment VIII: 3: ventral. 4: lateral. 5: abdominal segments VIII – X, dorsal. Figs. 6 – 7: abdominal segment IX: 6: lateral. 7: ventral. 8: phallus. Figs. 9 – 12, Metrichia pitu, n. sp., male genitalia: 9: lateral. 10: ventral. 11: dorsal. 12: phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189022/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
Fig. 
<number id="6B62CF311411FFB08C6A4A42EAA382AE" box="[369,387,1141,1167]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
). Sternum IX lengthened, produced, and lightly truncated anteriorly. Tergum IX short, rounded posteriorly, with a lobe that situates above the phallus; apex deeply cleft mesally (the cleft is narrow posteriorly and rounded at the base) (
<figureCitation id="4591C1931411FFB08F554AF5E9EE82FD" box="[590,718,1218,1244]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[232,1362,207,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[221,1372,197,1887]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Figs. 1 – 8, Alisotrichia cainguas, n. sp.: 1: Head, dorsal view. 2: Maxillary palp. Figs. 3 – 5, abdominal segment VIII: 3: ventral. 4: lateral. 5: abdominal segments VIII – X, dorsal. Figs. 6 – 7: abdominal segment IX: 6: lateral. 7: ventral. 8: phallus. Figs. 9 – 12, Metrichia pitu, n. sp., male genitalia: 9: lateral. 10: ventral. 11: dorsal. 12: phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189022/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
Figs. 
<number id="6B62CF311411FFB08F8B4AF5E9EE82FD" box="[656,718,1218,1244]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="10.0" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="9.0">9–11</number>
</figureCitation>
). Lateral appendages quadrangular, with the apex concave in lateral view. Cerci short and rounded. Dorsal appendages resembling curved, long spines, shorter than the dorsal lobe of segment IX. Phallus long, reaching segment II; with a pair of robust, strongly pigmented, apical spines; central tubule dark up to half its length (
<figureCitation id="4591C1931411FFB08FDD4B01E83E8371" box="[710,798,1334,1360]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 12" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1923,1947]" captionTargetBox="[232,1362,207,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[221,1372,197,1887]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 12. Figs. 1 – 8, Alisotrichia cainguas, n. sp.: 1: Head, dorsal view. 2: Maxillary palp. Figs. 3 – 5, abdominal segment VIII: 3: ventral. 4: lateral. 5: abdominal segments VIII – X, dorsal. Figs. 6 – 7: abdominal segment IX: 6: lateral. 7: ventral. 8: phallus. Figs. 9 – 12, Metrichia pitu, n. sp., male genitalia: 9: lateral. 10: ventral. 11: dorsal. 12: phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189022/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
Fig. 
<number id="6B62CF311411FFB08FE64B01E83E8371" box="[765,798,1334,1360]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="95B08E9D1411FFB08DDE4B6AEF6D808E" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="DD15DD161411FFB08DDE4B6AEFB98033" blockId="3.[151,1437,1063,1905]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis id="EFDE01041411FFB08DDE4B6AEA658356" bold="true" box="[197,325,1373,1399]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Based on the structure of the male genitalia this species seems to be more closely related to a group of species from Central 
<collectingCountry id="A5BD9D861411FFB08F124BB3E95383BF" box="[521,627,1412,1438]" name="United States of America" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">America</collectingCountry>
, than with the species known regionally, especially with 
<taxonomicName id="1AAAA6951411FFB0883E4BB3EA0583E5" authority="Flint 1968" authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Metrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis id="EFDE01041411FFB0883E4BB3EEBB83BC" box="[1317,1435,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">M. similis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="B93BA0E71411FFB08D844B9DEA3D83E5" author="Flint" box="[159,285,1450,1476]" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" refString="Flint, O. S., Jr. (1968) Bredin - Archbold - Smithsonian Biological Survey of Dominica. 9. The Trichoptera (caddisflies) of the Lesser Antilles. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 125, 1 - 86." type="journal article" year="1968">
Flint 
<number id="6B62CF311411FFB08DFA4B9DEA3D83E5" box="[225,285,1450,1476]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="1968.0">1968</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="A5BD9D861411FFB08C744B9DEAC783E5" box="[367,487,1450,1476]" name="Dominica" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Dominica</collectingCountry>
, whose males are characterized by having the segment X sclerotized and with a V-shaped cleft at the apex (absent in other known species of the genus); segment IX oval anteriorly, and lateral appendages, that are longer than the dorsal lobe, with a deep V-shaped cleft at the apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DD15DD161411FFB08DDE4816EF6D808E" blockId="3.[151,1437,1063,1905]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">
This is the 
<number id="6B62CF311411FFB08C4A4816EA40801A" box="[337,352,1569,1595]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="2.0">2</number>
nd species of 
<taxonomicName id="1AAAA6951411FFB08F1B4816E95A801B" box="[512,634,1569,1594]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Metrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EFDE01041411FFB08F1B4816E95A801B" box="[512,634,1569,1594]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">Metrichia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described from Salto Encantado Provincial Park. Previously 
<taxonomicName id="1AAAA6951411FFB088604816EAF48043" authority="Angrisano 2005" authorityName="Angrisano" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Metrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuniapiru">
<emphasis id="EFDE01041411FFB088604816EA2B8040" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="60">M. cuniapiru</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="B93BA0E71411FFB08C0F487FEAF48043" author="Angrisano" box="[276,468,1608,1634]" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" refString="Angrisano, E. B. &amp; Sganga, J. V. (2005) Contribution to the knowledge of Metrichia Ross from Argentina (Trichoptera: Hydroptilidae: Ochrotrichiini). Aquatic Insects, 27, 113 - 123." type="journal article" year="2005">
Angrisano 
<number id="6B62CF311411FFB08C83487FEAF48043" box="[408,468,1608,1634]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(in 
<bibRefCitation id="B93BA0E71411FFB08F1D487FE8698043" author="Angrisano" box="[518,841,1608,1634]" pageId="3" pageNumber="68" refString="Angrisano, E. B. &amp; Sganga, J. V. (2005) Contribution to the knowledge of Metrichia Ross from Argentina (Trichoptera: Hydroptilidae: Ochrotrichiini). Aquatic Insects, 27, 113 - 123." type="journal article" year="2005">
Angrisano &amp; Sganga 
<number id="6B62CF311411FFB08E10487FE8698043" box="[779,841,1608,1634]" pageId="3" pageNumber="60" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) was described. The latter differentiates from the new one by: tergum X membranous, lateral appendages wide, short, and relatively truncated at the apex, segment IX oval anteriorly, phallus without dark, conspicuous spines at the apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
